CONCORD, N.H. (AP) — Policy advocates and members of the public will be able to watch lawmakers work online next year, but they’ll have to show up in person if they want to participate in the process.Under the coronavirus state of emergency, lawmakers held public hearings online, taking comment by phone from interested parties. But with the Statehouse reopened and the emergency declaration lifted, calling in to testify is no longer an option.According to the latest House calendar, the 400-member House will use double rooms in the Legislative Office Building for public hearings to allow committee members to spread out. The hearings will be broadcast online.New Futures, a nonprofit group that advocates for health and wellness, has led a petition drive seeking remote access for the public. Officials argue that citizen voices are essential to the legislative process and that no one should have to risk illness to be heard.